 achievement of self-determinism, independence, and the will to exist. Shackel describes a cooperative effort by two universities, the state museum, the New Philadelphia Association, and numerous descendents to explore the history and archaeology of this unusual multi-racial community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCommunity lifexHistoryxIllinoisxNew Philadelphia. 0aCommunity lifezIllinoiszNew PhiladelphiaxHistory. 0aCultural pluralismxHistoryxIllinoisxNew Philadelphia. 0aCultural pluralismzIllinoiszNew PhiladelphiaxHistory. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)xIllinoisxNew Philadelphia. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zIllinoiszNew Philadelphia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947832423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520947832.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles